 Abstract 
 Productive (wasting very little while working or producing something) for Chinese combination and ordinary rice production is guessed using a dual (random/including random data points) edge of something/unexplored area (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 rotting model. Results show/tell about a big differences in technical and allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) between ordinary and combination rice 
 production, and point to/show significant (related to a large area) (wasting very little while working or producing something) differences in combination rice production, but not in ordinary rice production. Â© 1998 
 Elsevier Science B.V. 
 Keywords: Combination rice production; Ordinary rice production; (random/including random data points) edge of something/unexplored area (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 
 1. Introduction 
 
 The continuous creation/introduction of new 
 technology has been used as a standard for distinguishing a modem farming-based system from a traditional system (Schultz, 1964). However, in developing countries, some new farming-based technologies 
 have been only partially successful in improving 
 productive (wasting very little while working or producing something). This is often attributed to a 
 lack of ability and/ or desire to (change to make better/change to fit new conditions) input 
 levels on the part of producers, due to (state of knowing someone or something well) 
 with traditional farming-based systems (i.e., Schultz's 
 'poor but (producing a lot with very little waste)' guess) andI or the presence 
 of institutional and cultural restrictions (Ghatak and 
 lngerset, 1984). These (things to carefully think about) suggest that, in 
 some cases, there may exist a negative relationship 
 between technical progress in ordinary farming and (understood/made real/achieved) (wasting very little while working or producing something) gains. 
 
 * 
 
 Corresponding author. 
 
 This paper examines (wasting very little while working or producing something) for combination rice in 
 China. Rice is a very important crop in Chinese 
 farming. Since 1976, F1 blended varieties 1 have 
 become more and more important in Chinese rice production, relative to 'conventional' rice varieties, 
 which are mostly improved semi-dwarf varieties. 2 In 1990, about 40% of China's rice 
 was planted in combination rice (Lin, 1994). While combination 
 
 1 F combinations are a type of high cooperating with/producing/giving up variety of rice. The 
 1 
 production of F 1 combination seed involves a complicated three-line 
 method (Lin, l99la). First, a cytoplasmic male-(having no germs/unable to have children) parent plant 
 is located. This plant is then crossed with a maintainer line to 
 produce children/child that, while (having no germs/unable to have children), have desirable (related to tiny chemical assembly instructions inside of living things) (features/ qualities/ traits). These seeds are then crossed with a 'restorer' line to 
 produce F 1 seeds with (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy) self-fertilizing abilities. 
 2 Strictly speaking, ordinary rice varieties now being 
 used in China are not traditional in the Schultz sense but are 
 instead post 'green revolution' varieties. Therefore, the newer 
 combination rice vruieties are 'third generation' varieties. 
 
