 rice has been introduced to some other rice producing countries, China is the only country in the world 
 in which combination rice is widely used in commercial 
 production. 
 The Chinese government often influences the diffusion of new farming-based technologies according to 
 its independence goal. As a result, the importance of (wasting very little while working or producing something) (things to carefully think about) in the adoption 
 decision (related to/looking at/thinking about) combination rice at the (related to a large area) and 
 producer level is uncertain. The measurement of 
 technical and money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) for combination rice 
 production, and the relationship of (wasting very little while working or producing something) and 
 producer (how money affects people's lives) (features/ qualities/ traits) would be 
 useful in facing these issues. While other studies 
 have examined money-based issues related to the adoption and production of combination rice (e.g., He et al., 
 1984, 1987; Lin, 1991a,b, 1992, 1994), little attention has been given to the examination of (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 for combination rice production in China. 
 Most studies that examine (wasting very little while working or producing something) in developing country farming have focused on technical 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) (Bravo-Ureta and Pinheiro, 1993). While 
 physical working well (things to carefully think about) are important, 
 improvements in money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) will lead to 
 greater benefits to farming-based producers in these 
 countries. Previous studies have examined (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 in rice production for other developing countries 
 (e.g., Dawson et al., 1991; Kalirajan, 1991). However, few studies have examined the effects of technical change on (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 The first (or most important) purpose of this paper is to examine 
 the effects of technical change on (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) of 
 traditional and modem farming within the big picture 
 of rice production in China, (in other words), to provide a test of 
 Schultz's 'poor but (producing a lot with very little waste)' guess. In doing 
 so, both technical and money-based (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) are 
 carefully thought about/believed within the big picture  of technical change 
 (i.e., adoption of combination rice). A secondary goal 
 is to examine the linkage between (wasting very little while working or producing something) in rice 
 production and producer (how money affects people's lives) (features/ qualities/ traits) in order to provide information that may be 
 useful in analysing the effects of policies designed to 
 improve the working well of new farming-based technologies. 
 These goals are (accomplished or gained) through an examination of productive (wasting very little while working or producing something) for ordinary and 
 combination rice in China. Two edge of something/unexplored area production functions are guessed; one for ordinary rice and 
 
 one for combination rice. These functions are then used to 
 measure the degree of (wasting very little while working or producing something) for Chinese rice 
 production. 
 The rest of this paper is organized as follows. A brief review of edge of something/unexplored area production function 
 way(s) of doing things is given in Section 2. This is followed by a discussion of the (related to careful studying or deep thinking) model used 
 in the study, and a description of the study areas 
 and data. The results of the analysis are then presented and discussed. Section 6 summarizes the 
 study's findings and provides some ending/deciding comments. 
 
 2. (wasting very little while working or producing something) and edge of something/unexplored area production functions 
 Farrell (1957) tells the difference between technical and 
 allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) (or price (wasting very little while working or producing something)) in production through the use of a 'frontier' production function. Technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) is the ability to produce a 
 given level of output with a minimum amount of 
 inputs under certain technology. Allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) refers to the ability of choosing best input 
 levels for given factor prices. Money-based or total 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) is the product of technical and allocative 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something). An (money-based)/cheaply (producing a lot with very little waste) input-output 
 combination would be on both the edge of something/unexplored area function 
 and the (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) path. 
 Scientific studies of productive (wasting very little while working or producing something) have 
 used a variety of approaches in modelling edge of something/unexplored area 
 production functions; parametric vs. nonparametric, 
 pre-decided vs. (random/including random data points), and programming methods vs. (related to studying numbers) methods. Battese (1992) provides a 
 review of parametric (wasting very little while working or producing something) methods, both pre-decided and (random/including random data points). Bravo-Ureta and Pinheiro 
 (1993) provide a review of scientific studies relating 
 to farm level production (wasting very little while working or producing something) in developing 
 countries. 
 Given the other choice scientific tools available, the 
 choice as to the 'best' method is unclear. Little 
 difficult/strict/high quality analysis has been done in testing the 
 sensitivity of (wasting very little while working or producing something) measures to the choice of 
 way(s) of doing things. Bravo-Ureta and Rieger (1990) compare the results of pre-decided (both programming 
 and econometric analyses) and (random/including random data points) parametric 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) models for a sample of US dairy farms. 
 While the guesses from each approach differ (numbers-based), the ordinal (wasting very little while working or producing something) rankings of farms 
 
 X. Xu, S.R. Jeffrey/ Farming-based Money flow 18 ( 1998) 157-165 
 
 received/got from the different models appear to be quite 
 almost the same. This would suggest that, to a certain degree, 
 the choice between other choice modelling approaches 
 may be somewhat random. 
 
