 greater in the south than in the north. As shown in 
 Table 1, poor people in the south are better educated 
 than those in the north and central areas. Due to 
 the greater development of non-farm (away from cities) industry 
 in the south, farmers in this area also have much more off-farm income than those in the north 
 and the central areas (Table 1). 
 A big differences also exist among the three 
 areas in terms of relative input use in rice production. As shown in Table 1, the use of capital inputs is 
 highest in the south area (i.e., 29% greater than in 
 the north) and lowest in the north, while labour use 
 on a per hectare basis is lowest in the south (i.e., 
 17% lower than in the north) and greatest in the 
 north. Given these differences in the (features/ qualities/ traits) 
 of farming between the three rice production areas of Jiangsu area of control/area of land, the north is defined as a 
 traditional farming-based area while the central and 
 the south are classified as more modern farming-based 
 areas, for the purposes of this study. 
 In beginning and building on the sample for the farm household 
 survey, two counties are selected from each area 
 (i.e., south, central and north) on a random basis. 
 The six counties selected from this process are Wu, 
 jing and Jurong (south); Taixing and Jiandu (central), 
 and Huaiyin and Dafeny (north). Within each of 
 these counties, 15 ordinary rice farmers and 15 
 combination rice farmers are randomly selected as the 
 sample families for the survey. This results in a 
 total sample size of 180 rice families, distributed 
 over 33 villages in the six counties. 
 Each of these 180 families is surveyed with 
 respect to output levels and input use in rice production, as well as (how money affects people's lives) (features/ qualities/ traits). Rice 
 
 production and input data are collected on a per 
 hectare basis. Rice yield is expressed in terms of 
 metric tonjha. Data are collected for five productive 
 inputs; labour, chemical (material that makes plants grow better), manurial (material that makes plants grow better), 
 machinery and crop-watering/rinsing with water services, and bug-killers. 
 Labour use is expressed as day jha, with 1 day being 
 equal to 8 h of labour. Chemical (material that makes plants grow better) use is 
 measured as metric tons of total/totally/with nothing else mixed in nutrient per hectare, 
 while manurial (material that makes plants grow better) use is measured in value 
 terms, grouped by the local price. Machinery and 
 crop-watering/rinsing with water services are grouped using tractor service time. Bug-killers are measured in terms of kgjha. 
 In addition to input and output amounts, prices for 
 input and output are collected on a (related to a large area) average 
 basis. 
 (how money affects people's lives) (features/ qualities/ traits) are also collected 
 for the survey sample. These (features/ qualities/ traits) include 
 household size, total number of years of education 
 for household labour, average income from non-rice 
 farm sources, average non-farm income and total 
 area of rice production. These data are used in the 
 analysis to identify important (features/ qualities/ traits) influencing (wasting very little while working or producing something) of rice production. 
