 Some effects/results/suggestions may be drawn from the results 
 shown in Table 2. First, the constant term for the CR 
 function is higher than that for the HR function 
 (5.944 vs. 4.895). This lends believability to the view 
 that since CR varieties have been changed over time 
 for use in poor conditions with (compared to other things) low capital 
 input use, they have a higher 'basic' yield (Hayami 
 and Ruttan, 1985). Also, the (related to a large area) yield differences (taken/took by force)/(taken/took control of) by the dummy (numbers that change/things that change) (D 1 and D 2 ) 
 are much greater for HR production than for CR 
 production, especially for the south area. 
 The results in Table 2 also suggest that the response in HR production is much more elastic with 
 respect to chemical (material that makes plants grow better) and bug-killers than is 
 the case for CR production. This is also true to a 
 lesser extent for manurial (material that makes plants grow better) and machinery 
 services. The opposite is true for labour input use, 
 however. These results confirm the findings by Fan 
 (1991) that 'modem' inputs (e.g., chemical (material that makes plants grow better)s 
 
 and machinery services) are becoming more important for Chinese farming over time, (in other words), with the 
 increase in combination rice production. Overall, HR production is more (able to reply or react/quick to respond) to scale increases in the 
 five inputs modelled in the analysis, (in other words), the ability to stretch "of scale for the HR function is 0.804 vs. 0.387 for 
 CR production. 
