 (producing a lot with very little waste) with traditional varieties. 
 The other significant result that may be drawn 
 from Table 3 is that productive (wasting very little while working or producing something) is greater 
 in the south than in the north. (wasting very little while working or producing something) values for 
 the central area lie between those for the north and 
 south. This difference is consistent for both HR and 
 CR production, and for all three measures of productive (wasting very little while working or producing something). However, the watched/followed differences 
 are greater, on average, for HR production than for 
 CR production. 
 Relative to previous studies for other rice producing areas, Chinese rice production appears to display greater technical (wasting very little while working or producing something). For example, average technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) guesses for rice production 
 in the Philippines and Malaysia are 0.50 (Kalirajan 
 and Flinn, 1983) and 0.65 (Kalirajan and Shand, 
 1986), (match up each pair of items in order). These differences are not surprising, as production decisions in China during the 
 (connected/related) time period (i.e., mid-1980's) were mostly 
 controlled by local government, and a goal of the 
 Chinese government at that time was to (make as big as possible) 
 rice yield. Comparisons for allocative and money-based 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) are not made, as few studies 
 examine these parts of productive (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 The (wasting very little while working or producing something) calculations show/tell about a big differences among areas and poor people in HR production. Schumpterian explanation of money-based development 
 hints that technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) is influenced by 
 technical knowledge and understanding, as well as 
 by the (how money affects people's lives) (surrounding conditions) within which the 
 farmer must make decisions (Kalirajan, 1990). Based 
 on previous studies (Bravo-Ureta and Pinheiro, 
 1993 ), three (features/ qualities/ traits) are chosen as indicators 
 of this (how money affects people's lives) (surrounding conditions) and are (after that) used as explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) in the analysis 
 of productive (wasting very little while working or producing something) for HR production: (i) education, measured by average years of education for 
 household labour; (ii) land size, measured by the 
 total land area helped grow; and (iii) total household 
 
