 non-farming-based income. OLS procedures are used to 
 guess the relationship between productive (wasting very little while working or producing something) and these (features/ qualities/ traits). 
 The hidden (under) idea (you think is true) in this type of procedure is that the explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) are (coming from the outside of something) 
 to the decisions made by producers. While this is 
 likely true for land size and education, it is not 
 (usually/ in a common and regular way) the case for non-farm income. 6 Given the 
 differences between areas in terms of off-farm 
 employment opportunities, however, it may be argued that to a certain extent non-farm income is 
 (coming from the outside of something). Also, Kalirajan (1991) argues that 
 since (numbers that change/things that change) such as farm size, education and 
 non-farm income have indirect influences on technical (wasting very little while working or producing something), it is appropriate to include these in a 
 secondary analysis. 
 The results of this analysis are presented in Table 
 4. Overall, the explanatory ability of the three (numbers that change/things that change) included in the analysis is limited (i.e., R 2 
 values are usually less than 0.5), and not all (moving backwards) or limit/guideline guesses are significant. Education appears to be a significant factor in explaining 
 technical (wasting very little while working or producing something), but not as significant for allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something). A positive relationship appears to 
 exist between land size, and money-based and allocative 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) in modern farming-based areas (i.e., the 
 south), while the opposite is true for traditional 
 
 6 The authors thankfully admit/recognize/respond to the comments of an 
 unnamed reviewer for raising this issue. 
 
 farming-based areas (i.e., the north). This hints that 
 the mostly small farm sizes may present/ask/stand in a showy and fake way a 
 restriction to technical change in more modern areas, but not in more traditional farming-based production areas. A almost the same  analysis was conducted for CR 
 production, but no significant relationships were 
 found. 
 
 6. Ending/deciding comments and policy hint/result/effect 
 This paper uses a (random/including random data points) production and cost 
 edge of something/unexplored area to get technical, allocative and money-based 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) of Chinese ordinary rice and combination 
 rice production. The results suggest that while HR 
 production increases the potential (making a lot of an item so each item costs less) 
 for Chinese rice production, watched/followed productive 
 (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) are lower than for CR production. The 
 results of this study are agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with 'poor but 
 (producing a lot with very little waste)' guess; poor people are (producing more with less waste) in 
 setting apart inputs for CR production than for HR 
 production. This is consistent for both modern and 
 traditional farming-based areas. 
 Facing increasing population pressures, China has 
 put into use policies designed to improve technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) and total working well. This study shows/tells about a 
 positive relationship between (wasting very little while working or producing something) and education for HR production, this way, focusing on the importance of (thinking about/when one thinks about) poor people' abilities to receive and 
 understand information relating to new farming-based 
 technology. This study also decides/figures out that land size 
 
 X. Xu, S.R. Jeffrey/ Farming-based Money flow 18 (1998) 157-165 
 
 is a positive factor in explaining the (wasting very little while working or producing something) of HR 
 in modern farming-based areas. This hints that in 
 modern farming-based areas, the mostly small 
 farm size may present/ask/stand in a showy and fake way a self-control/control device to technical change 
 and so, supports the argument for further (easing government rules) in land markets. 
 
